<p>In late April to early May 2026, a major shift occurred in EU AI governance: <strong>EU legislators agreed to delay high-risk AI rules</strong> while introducing an AI Act "Omnibus Simplification Package."</p>

<p>The news has triggered two conflicting interpretations: one camp sees "regulatory relief," while the other warns that "rules are more complex, just in a different form."</p>

<h2>What Happened</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>August 2024</strong>: EU AI Act enters into force, with phased implementation</li>
  <li><strong>February 2025</strong>: High-risk AI system rules begin application</li>
  <li><strong>April 2026</strong>: Commission proposes Omnibus simplification — delaying high-risk rules, reducing SME burden, narrowing AI definition</li>
  <li><strong>Early May 2026</strong>: Member states and lawmakers fail to reach final deal on details (Reuters), but direction is set</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Challenge: A Regulatory Rebalance, Not a Retreat</h2>

<p>The IAPP analysis identifies three adjustments: <strong>what is AI, who needs oversight, and how to enforce.</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Narrower AI definition</strong> — excluding rule-based systems, focusing on systems with genuine autonomous decision-making</li>
  <li><strong>Slower implementation</strong> — extended deadlines for high-risk AI compliance</li>
  <li><strong>Clearer liability chain</strong> — better defined responsibilities between foundation model providers and deployers</li>
</ul>

<h2>What This Means for Enterprises</h2>

<p><strong>Good news</strong>: More transition time (especially for finance, healthcare, HR AI applications); ~40% reduced documentation requirements; broader SME exemptions.</p>

<p><strong>Challenges</strong>: "Simplification" ≠ "simple" — companies need to re-understand AI classification standards; compliance paths have changed but the destination hasn't; enforcement divergence across member states.</p>

<h2>Convergence with China's Approach</h2>

<p>Interestingly, the EU's simplification direction converges with China's regulatory thinking — both moving from "blanket regulation" toward "risk-classified management." For cross-Eurasia enterprises: core compliance elements are converging (transparency, risk management, human oversight), but specific paths and language differ.</p>

<h2>Looking Ahead</h2>

<p>JD Supra's assessment is apt: "The Omnibus simplification isn't the end of the AI Act — it's its coming of age." AI governance is shifting from a "legislative paradigm" to an "enforcement paradigm." The real test is how rules are interpreted and enforced in real business environments.</p>

<p>For Chinese and multinational companies deploying AI: don't wait for final clarity — start building AI governance frameworks now; risk classification is central; human-in-the-loop is evolving from recommendation to requirement.</p>

